#X text 78 24 Time to check a real worls example. This is not much different than what we've seen with other techniques. The key idea is to modulate the sound for a rich and evolving timbre and the important factor in waveshaping \, as shown before \, is controlling the amplitude into the waveshaper. Below to the left we have a decay envelope controlling the gain of a sine wave going into a cosine waveshaper and a drive (tanh) distortion. Plus some reverb for a final touch., f 45;
#X obj 469 435 decay~ 500;
#X obj 382 475 *~ 1;
#X obj 554 396 decay~ 1500;
#X obj 554 427 *~ 5000;
#X obj 554 458 +~ 250;
#X text 441 16 And of course we can combine with other techniques. Below to the right we also stack a sawtooth and and a filter modulation (hence \, subtractive synthesis). Note that the [moog~] object also has a 'drive' parameter \, which is a 'tanh' approximation inside its feedback loop as discussed before (so it's also related to waveshaphing / distortion). Below we control this parameter with a LFO., f 38;
